     <theorem xml:id="theorem-limits-polynomials">
        <title>General Limits of Polynomials</title>
        <statement>
            <p>If  <m>p(x)</m> is a polynomial and <m>c</m> is a real number, then <m>\lim_{x \to c} p(x) = p(c)</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </theorem>
        <activity xml:id="activity-limits-polynomials">
        <statement>
            <p> Given <m>p(x)=-3x^2-5x+7</m> and <m>q(x)=x^4-x^2+3</m>, which of the following describes the limit properties that can best be used to determine <m>\lim_{x \to -1} \frac{p(x)}{q(x)}</m>?
            </p>
       <ol label="A">
                <li>Sums/differences, scalar multiples, and products properties </li> 
                <li> <xref ref="theorem-limits-polynomials"/> and the quotient property of limits </li>
                <li>Powers, sums/differences, scalar multiples, and constants properties</li>
                <li>Quotients and roots properties</li>

            </ol>
        </statement>
    </activity>
    <theorem xml:id="theorem-limits-rationals">
    <title>General Limits of Rational Functions </title>
        <statement>
        <p>If <m>p(x)</m> and <m>q(x)</m> are polynomials, <m>c</m> is a real number, and <m>q(c) \neq 0</m> then <m>\lim_{x \to c} \frac{p(x)}{q(x)}=\frac{p(c)}{q(c)}</m>.</p>
        </statement>
    </theorem>
    <activity xml:id="activity-limits-rationals">
        <statement><p>One of the requirements to <xref ref="theorem-limits-rationals"/> when taking the limit of a rational function <m>\frac{p(x)}{q(x)}</m> as <m>x \to c</m> was that we cannot have <m>q(c)=0</m>. Is it possible for <m>\lim_{x \to c}\frac{p(x)}{q(x)} </m> to exist if <m>q(c)=0</m>?</p> 
  <ol label="A">
            <li>No, because <m>\frac{p(x)}{q(x)}</m> is not defnied at <m>x=c</m> since <m>q(c)=0</m>.</li>
            <li>Yes, because if you graph <m>f(x)=\frac{x^2-1}{x-1}</m>, the value <m>f(1)</m> is not defined, but the graph shows that the limit of <m>f(x)</m> does exist as <m>x \to 1</m>.</li>
            <li>No, because if you graph <m>g(x)=\frac{x^2+1}{x-1}</m>, the value <m>g(1)</m> is not defined and the graph shows that the limit of <m>\lim_{x \to c}g(x)</m> does not exist.</li>
            <li>Yes, because <xref ref="theorem-limits-rationals"/> does not say anything about the existence of <m>\lim_{x \to c}\frac{p(x)}{q(x)}</m> when <m>q(c)=0</m>.</li>
        </ol>
        </statement>
    </activity>

